  "text": ". FMD was significantly reduced in smokers (P, 0·05) and there was a significant positive relationship between n-3 PUFA status and FMD in smokers (P, 0·01), which was not present in non-smokers [CITATION_1] ; . there were significant positive relationships between FMD and n-3 PUFA status in those subjects in the top one-third for fasting glucose, insulin and triacylglycerol levels with no relationships in those with lower levels [CITATION_2] ; . neither plasma vitamin E concentrations (alone or adjusted for lipid concentrations) nor total antioxidant status were related to any of the measures of vascular function [CITATION_3] ; . in the group as a whole, FMD was similar for the different endothelial NO synthase genotypes [CITATION_4] ; . there were no significant differences in FMD between smokers and non-smokers with the Glu/Glu genotype, whereas in subjects with Glu/Asp and Asp/Asp genotypes the smokers had a significantly reduced FMD (P, 0·01; [CITATION_5] ; . there was a significant relationship between n-3 PUFA status and FMD in Glu/Asp and Asp/Asp subjects (P, 0·05), but not in those with the Glu/Glu genotype [CITATION_6] ).",
